{"questionId":"22646123","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Gundega claims that, on average, Latvian women are taller than Dutch women.</p>\n<p>Random samples of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math> Latvian women and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math> Dutch women are chosen, and their heights are measured.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/0fed9ec60607dcd5ba3d0ff6405cef575c6eac18.png\" width=\"580\" height=\"152\"></p>\n<p>Gundega performs a <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>-test at the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mo>%</mo></math> significance level. It is assumed that the populations are normally distributed and have equal variances.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>82</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>21</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22646123","referenceCode":"24M.2.SL.TZ2.4ci","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"a.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.11—Expected, observed, hypotheses, chi squared, gof, t-test"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":3}
